Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
monitor_hosts(25.10)                                      monitor_hosts(25.10)

Name
       monitor_hosts

Syntax
       monitor_hosts

       [-help]

       [-log <string>]

       [-overwrite]

       [-period <integer>]

       Monitors  hosts  and  periodically  prints the memory or CPU usage, and
       temporary disk speed of the hosts. This  command  automatically  deter-
       mines  the  hosts  to  be monitored. By default, after every 60 seconds
       hosts are monitored and the disk information is written to a log file.

       This command is helpful to analyze and debug the performance of a  ses-
       sion  and helps check the machine load, the available memory, and track
       possible reasons for a slow down or unexpected exit during a session.

       The monitor_hosts command is supported in STA, DSTA, and DMMMC flows.

       The monitor_hosts command output is described below:

       ________________________________________________________

       | Status     |  Memory     |  CPU Usage  |  Disk       |

       |  Keys/Tags |   (%age     |             |   Speed     |

       |            |  of         |             |   (Mb/sec)  |

       |            |   Available |             |             |

       |            |   Memory on |             |             |

       |            |   the       |             |             |

       |            |   correspon |             |             |

       |            |  ding host) |             |             |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       | E -        |  Memory     |  CPU Usage  |  Disk       |

       |  Excellent |   used less |  less       |   speed     |

       |            |   than 75%  |  than 85%   |   more than |

       |            |             |             |   250       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       | G - Good   |  Memory     |  CPU Usage  |  Disk       |

       |            |   used      |  between    |   speed     |

       |            |   between   |   85% to    |   between   |

       |            |   75% and   |   95%       |   125 and   |

       |            |   85%       |             |   250       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       | B - Bad    |  Memory     |  CPU Usage  |  Disk       |

       |  (*)       |   used      |  between    |   speed     |

       |            |   between   |   95% to    |   between   |

       |            |   85% and   |   105%      |   50 and    |

       |            |   99%       |             |   125       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       | T -        |  Memory     |  CPU Usage  |  Disk       |

       |            |   used      |  more       |   speed     |

       | Terrible   |   above 99% |  than 105%  |   less than |

       |  (**)      |             |             |   50        |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       The monitor_hosts command output will show host/machine specific infor-
       mation and not process specific information. So if  multiple  processes
       are  running on the same machine, then the command output will show the
       combined impact of all the processes,  on  the  machine's  memory,  ma-
       chine's CPU usage etc.

       The "T" or "B" state denotes that a session may be thrashing or may not
       give  the best results with respect to the performance. For better per-
       formance, you must re-run this command with better machines.

       Parameters

       -help  Prints out the command usage. For a detailed description of  the
              command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man mon-
              itor_hosts.

       -log <string>
              Specifies the log file name.

              Default: host-monitor.log

       -overwrite
              Overwrites the log file, if it already exists.

       -period <integer>
              Specifies  the  sampling  period after which hosts will be moni-
              tored.

              Default: 60

       Examples

              * A sample monitor log file is shown below:

                Status keys: E excellent, G good, B bad, T terrible.

                Memory values:

                total = Real memory of host

                progs = Real memory used  by  processes,  including  swappable
                cache

                used  =  Real  memory  used  by processes, excluding swappable
                cache

